{"title_page": "Mkhitar Heratsi", "text_new": "[[File:\u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580 \u0540\u0565\u0580\u0561\u0581\u0578\u0582 \u056f\u056b\u057d\u0561\u0576\u0564\u0580\u056b4.jpg|thumb|Bust of Mkhitar Heratsi]]\n'''Mkhitar Heratsi''' ({{lang-hy|\u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580 \u0540\u0565\u0580\u0561\u0581\u056b}}) was a 12th-century [[Armenians|Armenian]] physician. He was born in [[Khoy]] (present-day northwestern [[Iran]]).<ref name=\"Hacikyan427\">Agop Jack Hacikyan, Gabriel Basmajian, Edward S. Franchuk, Nourhan Ouzounian. [https://books.google.nl/books?id=2gZzD0N9Id8C&pg=PA427&dq=mkhitar+heratsi+khoy&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI2cWP69KKxgIVoxbbCh1CfQC9#v=onepage&q=mkhitar%20heratsi%20khoy&f=false \"The Heritage of Armenian Literature: From the sixth to the eighteenth century\"] Wayne State University Press, 2002. p 427</ref> Heratsi, is often being called the father of [[Armenian medicine]],<ref>https://folklife.si.edu/talkstory/healing-herbs-folk-remedies-in-armenia \"In the twelfth century, the father of Armenian medicine, Mkhitar Heratsi, authored his pivotal book on fevers\" (article from the [[Smithsonian Institution]] website)</ref><ref>https://medium.com/@raffielliottian/10-reasons-why-armenia-has-become-a-medical-tourism-mecca-dadf22fd532f \"Mkhitar Heratsi, known as the 'father of Armenian medicine' greatly contributed to the medical fields of surgery, diet, and psychotherapy.\"</ref><ref>https://www.crwflags.com/FOTW/flags/am-yerev.html \"Yerevan State Medical University...was named in honor of Mkhitar Heratsi (1110/1120-1200), the father of Armenian medicine and author of the Relief of Fevers encyclopedia (1184)\"</ref><ref>https://www.armenian-history.com/28-armenian-history/harticles/65-medicine-in-ancient-and-medieval-armeniamenia.html \"Mekhitar Heratsi...was the founder of medieval Armenian medicine. He played the same role in Armenian medicine as Hippocrates did for Greek, Galen for Roman and Ibn Sina for Arab medicine.\"</ref> was the author of the ''[[Relief of Fevers]]'', an encyclopedic work in which he discussed, among other subjects, [[surgery]], [[diet (nutrition)|diet]] and [[psychotherapy]]. \n\n[[Yerevan State Medical University]] is named after Heratsi. The most prominent students of [[YSMU]] are awarded with \"Mkhitar Heratsi [[scholarship]]\".\n\nHe was well versed in the [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Greek language|Greek]], and [[Arabic language|Arabic]] languages.<ref name=\"Hacikyan427\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ysmu.am The website of Yerevan State Medical University after Mkhitar Heratsi]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heratsi, Mikhitar}}\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Armenian scientists]]\n[[Category:Medieval Armenian physicians]]\n[[Category:Armenian academics]]\n[[Category:People from Khoy]]\n\n\n{{Armenia-bio-stub}}\n{{Iran-bio-stub}}\n{{med-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:\u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580 \u0540\u0565\u0580\u0561\u0581\u0578\u0582 \u056f\u056b\u057d\u0561\u0576\u0564\u0580\u056b4.jpg|thumb|Bust of Mkhitar Heratsi]]\n'''Mkhitar Heratsi''' ({{lang-hy|\u0544\u056d\u056b\u0569\u0561\u0580 \u0540\u0565\u0580\u0561\u0581\u056b}}) was a 12th-century [[Armenians|Armenian]] physician. He was born in [[Khoy]] (present-day northwestern [[Iran]]).<ref name=\"Hacikyan427\">Agop Jack Hacikyan, Gabriel Basmajian, Edward S. Franchuk, Nourhan Ouzounian. [https://books.google.nl/books?id=2gZzD0N9Id8C&pg=PA427&dq=mkhitar+heratsi+khoy&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI2cWP69KKxgIVoxbbCh1CfQC9#v=onepage&q=mkhitar%20heratsi%20khoy&f=false \"The Heritage of Armenian Literature: From the sixth to the eighteenth century\"] Wayne State University Press, 2002. p 427</ref> Heratsi, often called the father of [[Armenian medicine]],<ref>https://folklife.si.edu/talkstory/healing-herbs-folk-remedies-in-armenia \"In the twelfth century, the father of Armenian medicine, Mkhitar Heratsi, authored his pivotal book on fevers\" (article from the [[Smithsonian Institution]] website)</ref><ref>https://medium.com/@raffielliottian/10-reasons-why-armenia-has-become-a-medical-tourism-mecca-dadf22fd532f \"Mkhitar Heratsi, known as the 'father of Armenian medicine' greatly contributed to the medical fields of surgery, diet, and psychotherapy.\"</ref><ref>https://www.crwflags.com/FOTW/flags/am-yerev.html \"Yerevan State Medical University...was named in honor of Mkhitar Heratsi (1110/1120-1200), the father of Armenian medicine and author of the Relief of Fevers encyclopedia (1184)\"</ref><ref>https://www.armenian-history.com/28-armenian-history/harticles/65-medicine-in-ancient-and-medieval-armeniamenia.html \"Mekhitar Heratsi...was the founder of medieval Armenian medicine. He played the same role in Armenian medicine as Hippocrates did for Greek, Galen for Roman and Ibn Sina for Arab medicine.\"</ref> was the author of the ''[[Relief of Fevers]]'', a cyclopedic work in which he discussed, among other subjects, [[surgery]], [[diet (nutrition)|diet]] and [[psychotherapy]]. [[Yerevan State Medical University]] is named after Heratsi. The most prominent students of [[YSMU]] are awarded with \"Mkhitar Heratsi [[scholarship]]\".\n\nHe was well versed in the [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Greek language|Greek]], and [[Arabic language|Arabic]] languages.<ref name=\"Hacikyan427\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ysmu.am The website of Yerevan State Medical University after Mkhitar Heratsi]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heratsi, Mikhitar}}\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Armenian scientists]]\n[[Category:Medieval Armenian physicians]]\n[[Category:Armenian academics]]\n[[Category:People from Khoy]]\n\n\n{{Armenia-bio-stub}}\n{{Iran-bio-stub}}\n{{med-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tigran Panasyan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mkhitar_Heratsi"}
{"title_page": "Sungai Siput", "text_new": "{{for|the federal constituency represented in the Dewan Rakyat|Sungai Siput (federal constituency)}}\n'''Sungai Siput''' ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc8 \u0b9a\u0bc0\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bcd) is a town, [[mukim]] in [[Kuala Kangsar District]], [[Perak]], [[Malaysia]], covering 155.141 hectares, 61.5% of the total area of Kuala Kangsar. It is located about 25&nbsp;km from state capital, [[Ipoh]] and 20&nbsp;km from royal town of [[Kuala Kangsar]]. Sungai Siput falls under the management of the [[Kuala Kangsar Municipal Council]].\n\n== History ==\nThe earliest settlement in Sungai Siput was situated at Pelang, about 2 kilometres from the current town. The settlement was populated by villagers of [[Minangkabau people|Minangkabau]] origins who had earlier settled in Sayong Kuala Kangsar Perak. The settlers were from the family of Malik and the son Tuyub, which family tomb is still visible from the roadside situated in the estate in front of the Rimba Panjang new village. One the descendants was the late Imam Jusuh, one of the first imams of the Alghufraniah Sungai Siput Mosque and the town councillor. Sister Enson was a well-known traditional healer. One of the surviving siblings is Associate Professor Suhaimi Bin Saidin, a lecturer at [[Universiti Sultan Azlan Shah]] in [[Kuala Kangsar]]. With the arrival of British planters and tin miners in the early 1850s the focus of activity moved to the present Sungai Siput town.\n\n[[File:Chin Peng wanted by Malaya.jpg|thumb|]]\nSungai Siput is notable for the incident that triggered the start of the [[Malayan Emergency]]. The Malayan colonial administration declared a [[state of emergency]] on 16 June 1948 after members of the [[Communist Party of Malaya]] killed three European plantation managers at a plantation office twenty miles east of Sungai Siput town. The CPM was subsequently banned in July. Many [[Singapore]]an historians and [[anti-communist]]s allege that [[Chin Peng]] ordered the killings. Chin Peng claims he had no prior knowledge. In fact, he says he was so unprepared for the start of hostility that he barely escaped arrest, losing his passport in the process, and lost touch with the party for a couple of days.<ref>Chin Peng, ''My Side of History'', pp 215-222.</ref>\n\nLi Weilun, an [[Esperanto]] professor at the [[Beijing Language and Culture University]], was born in Sungai Siput in 1936.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espero.com.cn/2013-07/19/content_29470963.htm |title=Esperanto kaj la vivo en la Pekina Lingva Universitato |last=Fiocchi |first=Pietro |date= 2013-07-19 |website=El Popola \u0108inio |publisher= |access-date= 2017-12-19 |quote=Nia samideano naski\u011dis en 1936 en Malajzio, en la urbo Sungai Sipud. }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"3\"| Ethnic groups in Sungai Siput , 2010 census\n|-\n! [[Ethnicity]] !! Population !! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] || 18,255 || 37.3%\n|-\n| [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] || 15,745 || 32.1%\n|-\n| [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] || 13,439 || 27.5%\n|-\n| Others || 113 || 0.2%\n|-\n| Non-citizens || 1,402 || 2.9%\n|-\n! Total || 48,954 || 100%\n|}\n\n== Locations ==\nMahatma Gandhi Kalasalai Tamil School is the biggest [[Tamil language|Tamil]] school in the state with over 1000 students. The school's construction was commissioned by Tun [[V. T. Sambanthan]] in 1954 and was officially opened by [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]], former [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]]'s sister.\n\nSungai Siput is also famous for its groundnuts and can easily be bought in one of the shops along the main street.\n[[File:Sg-siput-town.jpg|thumb|left|View of Sungai Siput town]]\n\n== Politics ==\nThe Sungai Siput parliamentary seat has consistently voted for [[Alliance Party (Malaysia)|Alliance]] and later [[Barisan Nasional]] candidates since independence. However, in the [[Malaysian general election, 2008|2008 Malaysian general election]] was won Dr Jeyakumar Devaraj, a [[Parti Sosialis Malaysia]] member who contested under the [[Parti Keadilan Rakyat|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) ticket in the [[Pakatan Rakyat]] coalition. Dr [[Michael Jeyakumar Devaraj]] defeated the previous incumbent, Dato Seri [[Samy Vellu]], who had held the seat since 1974. The seat was successfully defended by PKR in the [[2018 Malaysian general election]].\n\n==Education==\n\nSchools in Sungai Siput, Perak\n\nThis is a list of schools in Sungai Siput, Perak.\n*Methodist Primary School\n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Methodist\n*Sekolah Menengah Jenis Kebangsaan (SMJK) Shing Chung\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Sungai Siput\n*SJK(C) Sungai Buloh\n*SJKT TUN Sambanthan Ladang SG.Siput\n*SMK Tok Muda Abdul Aziz\n*SJK(T) HEAWOOD SUNGAI SIPUT\n*SK(T) Mahathma Gandhi Kalasalai\n*SJK(C) Hing Wa\n*SK Lintang\n*SMK Datuk Haji Abdul Wahab\n*SUNGAI SIPUT THIRUMURAI CLASS\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tamil population by cities]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Perak}}\n\n{{coord|4|49|12|N|101|4|12|E|type:city_region:MY_source:nlwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Perak]]\n[[Category:Mukims of Perak]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the federal constituency represented in the Dewan Rakyat|Sungai Siput (federal constituency)}}\n'''Sungai Siput''' ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc8 \u0b9a\u0bc0\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bcd) is a town, [[mukim]] in [[Kuala Kangsar District]], [[Perak]], [[Malaysia]], covering 155.141 hectares, 61.5% of the total area of Kuala Kangsar. It is located about 25&nbsp;km from state capital, [[Ipoh]] and 20&nbsp;km from royal town of [[Kuala Kangsar]]. Sungai Siput falls under the management of the [[Kuala Kangsar Municipal Council]].\n\n== History ==\nThe earliest settlement in Sungai Siput was situated at Pelang, about 2 kilometres from the current town. The settlement was populated by villagers of [[Minangkabau people|Minangkabau]] origins who had earlier settled in Sayong Kuala Kangsar Perak. The settlers were from the family of Malik and the son Tuyub, which family tomb is still visible from the roadside situated in the estate in front of the Rimba Panjang new village. One the descendants was the late Imam Jusuh, one of the first imams of the Alghufraniah Sungai Siput Mosque and the town councillor. Sister Enson was a well-known traditional healer. One of the surviving siblings is Associate Professor Suhaimi Bin Saidin, a lecturer at [[Universiti Sultan Azlan Shah]] in [[Kuala Kangsar]]. With the arrival of British planters and tin miners in the early 1850s the focus of activity moved to the present Sungai Siput town.\n\n[[File:Chin Peng wanted by Malaya.jpg|thumb|]]\nSungai Siput is notable for the incident that triggered the start of the [[Malayan Emergency]]. The Malayan colonial administration declared a [[state of emergency]] on 16 June 1948 after members of the [[Communist Party of Malaya]] killed three European plantation managers at a plantation office twenty miles east of Sungai Siput town. The CPM was subsequently banned in July. Many [[Singapore]]an historians and [[anti-communist]]s allege that [[Chin Peng]] ordered the killings. Chin Peng claims he had no prior knowledge. In fact, he says he was so unprepared for the start of hostility that he barely escaped arrest, losing his passport in the process, and lost touch with the party for a couple of days.<ref>Chin Peng, ''My Side of History'', pp 215-222.</ref>\n\nLi Weilun, an [[Esperanto]] professor at the [[Beijing Language and Culture University]], was born in Sungai Siput in 1936.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espero.com.cn/2013-07/19/content_29470963.htm |title=Esperanto kaj la vivo en la Pekina Lingva Universitato |last=Fiocchi |first=Pietro |date= 2013-07-19 |website=El Popola \u0108inio |publisher= |access-date= 2017-12-19 |quote=Nia samideano naski\u011dis en 1936 en Malajzio, en la urbo Sungai Sipud. }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"3\"| Ethnic groups in Sungai Siput , 2010 census\n|-\n! [[Ethnicity]] !! Population !! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] || 18,255 || 37.3%\n|-\n| [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] || 15,745 || 32.1%\n|-\n| [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] || 13,439 || 27.5%\n|-\n| Others || 113 || 0.2%\n|-\n| Non-citizens || 1,402 || 2.9%\n|-\n! Total || 48,954 || 100%\n|}\n\n== Locations ==\nMahatma Gandhi Kalasalai Tamil School is the biggest [[Tamil language|Tamil]] school in the state with over 1000 students. The school's construction was commissioned by Tun [[V. T. Sambanthan]] in 1954 and was officially opened by [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]], former [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]]'s sister.\n\nSungai Siput is also famous for its groundnuts and can easily be bought in one of the shop along the main street.\n[[File:Sg-siput-town.jpg|thumb|left|View of Sungai Siput town]]\n\n== Politics ==\nThe Sungai Siput parliamentary seat has consistently voted for [[Alliance Party (Malaysia)|Alliance]] and later [[Barisan Nasional]] candidates since independence. However, in the [[Malaysian general election, 2008|2008 Malaysian general election]] was won Dr Jeyakumar Devaraj, a [[Parti Sosialis Malaysia]] member who contested under the [[Parti Keadilan Rakyat|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) ticket in the [[Pakatan Rakyat]] coalition. Dr [[Michael Jeyakumar Devaraj]] defeated the previous incumbent, Dato Seri [[Samy Vellu]], who had held the seat since 1974. The seat was successfully defended by PKR in the [[2018 Malaysian general election]].\n\n==Education==\n\nSchools in Sungai Siput (U), Perak\n\nThis is a list of schools in Sungai Siput (U), Perak.\n*Methodist Primary School\n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Methodist\n*Sekolah Menengah Jenis Kebangsaan (SMJK) Shing Chung\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Sungai Siput\n*SJK(C) Sungai Buloh\n*SJKT TUN Sambanthan Ladang SG.Siput\n*SMK Tok Muda Abdul Aziz\n*SJK)T) HEAWOOD SUNGAI SIPUT\n*SK(T) Mahathma Gandhi Kalasalai\n*SJK(C) Hing Wa\n*SK Lintang\n*SMK Datuk Haji Abdul Wahab\n*SUNGAI SIPUT THIRUMURAI CLASS\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tamil population by cities]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Perak}}\n\n{{coord|4|49|12|N|101|4|12|E|type:city_region:MY_source:nlwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Perak]]\n[[Category:Mukims of Perak]]\n", "name_user": "Sezhian6911", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sungai_Siput"}
{"title_page": "Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park\n| iucn_category = III\n| photo = Pfeiffer Beach Stream.jpg\n| photo_caption = Looking back from the beach at Pfeiffer Beach in California\n| map = USA California#USA\n| relief = 1\n| location = [[Monterey County, California]], United States\n| nearest_city = [[Big Sur, California]]\n| coords = {{Coord|36|15|N|121|47|W|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n| area_acre = 1000\n| established =\n| visitation_num =\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[California Department of Parks and Recreation]]\n}}\n\n'''Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park''' is a [[state park]] in [[Monterey County, California|Monterey County]], [[California]], near the area of [[Big Sur]] on the [[U.S. state|state's]] [[Central Coast, California|Central Coast]]. It covers approximately {{convert|1006|acre|km2}} of land. The park is centered on the [[Big Sur River]]. It has been nicknamed a \"mini Yosemite.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seemonterey.com/big-sur-california/pfeiffer-big-sur-state-park-big-sur-california|title= Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Pfeiffer homestead.jpg|thumb|upright|John Pfeiffer's cabin, 2006]]\n\nThe first known European settler in Big Sur was George Davis, who in 1853 claimed a tract of land along the Big Sur River. He built a cabin near the present day site of the beginning of the Mount Manuel Trail.<ref name=\"henson\">{{cite web|last1=Henson|first1=Paul|author2=Donald J. Usner|title=The Natural History of Big Sur|url=http://sulcus.berkeley.edu/wjf/m/NaturalHistoryOfBigSur.pdf|publisher=University Of California Press|access-date=12 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617070622/http://sulcus.berkeley.edu/wjf/m/NaturalHistoryOfBigSur.pdf |archivedate= June 17, 2010|date=1993}}</ref>{{rp|326}} In 1868, Native Americans Manual and Florence Innocenti bought Davis' cabin and land for $50. \n\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park is named after John Pfeiffer, who lived in a cabin on the property beginning in 1884. He was the son of Michael Pfeiffer and Barbara Laquet. The Pfeiffer family family immigrated from France. Their son and his family were among the first European settlers in the area. In the winter of 1869, Michael and Barbara Laquet Pfeiffer were on their way to the south coast of Big Sur when they were forced to stop for the season in the Sycamore Canyon area near present-day Big Sur Village. They liked the area so much they decided against moving south again the following spring. They brought four children with them: Charles, John, Mary Ellen, and Julia. They later had four more:  William, Frank, Flora, and Adelaide. After the [[Homestead Acts#Homestead Act of 1862|Homestead Act of 1862]] was passed by Congress, he filed for patents on his land in 1883 and 1889.<ref>{{cite web |title=Micheal Pfeiffer of Monterey County {{!}} 2 Land Patents |url=https://thelandpatents.com/owners/1112682 |website=The Land Patents |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hikinginbigsur.com/hikes_oakgrove.html|title= Hiking in Big Sur - Oak Grove Trail Loop|website=HikingInBigSur.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Many features in Big Sur are named for the descendants of the Pfeiffers.\n\nIn 1930, John Pfeiffer was offered $210,000 for his land by a Los Angeles developer who intended to build a subdivision. Pfeiffer wanted to preserve the land he and his family had grown to love, and instead sold {{convert|700|acre|km2}} to the state of California in 1933.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Heid|first1=Analise Elliot|title=Hiking & backpacking Big Sur : a complete guide to the trails of Big Sur, Ventana Wilderness, and Silver Peak Wilderness|date=2013|publisher=Wilderness Press|isbn=978-0899977270|page=84|edition=Second}}</ref>\n\nIn 1934, the [[Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council#History|Monterey Bay Area Council]] built a makeshift Camp Wing within the park, but it was abandoned after the 1937 summer camping season. The next year the Boy Scouts built Camp Esselen at another location within the park. This site was improved until 1945, when limitations of the site, closeness to public camping facilities, and jurisdictional conflicts between the Scouts and the state forced the council to request reimbursement from the state for $8,000 in improvements. The council continued to use the camp until 1953. In 1952, the Scouts began building [[Camp Pico Blanco]], and when that camp was opened in 1954, Camp Esselen was finally closed.<ref name=\"leaders\">{{cite web|url=http://camppicoblanco.org/pico/downloads/2016_camp_pico_blanco_leaders_guide/|title=2017 Camp Pico Blanco Scout Reservation Leader's Guide|publisher=Monterey Bay Area Council, Boy Scouts of America|location=Salinas, California|accessdate=September 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906001953/http://camppicoblanco.org/pico/downloads/2016_camp_pico_blanco_leaders_guide/|archivedate=September 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"men\">{{cite news|url=http://whitestag.org/files/men_in_the_making.pdf|title=The Making of Men|last=Young|first=Alfred|date=July 1963|publisher=Monterey Bay Area Council|location=Salinas, California|accessdate=August 13, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201153140/http://whitestag.org/files/men_in_the_making.pdf|archivedate=December 1, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Overnight stays==\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park has both a hotel (the Big Sur Lodge) and a campground within its boundaries. The campgrounds were closed in the winter of 2008\u20132009 due to the [[Basin Complex Fire]]. The campgrounds have coin-operated showers, bathrooms and a convenience store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seemonterey.com/big-sur-california/pfeiffer-big-sur-state-park-big-sur-california|title= Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park}}</ref> The convenience store also offers WiFi access.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parks.ca.gov/default.asp?page_id=570 |title=California State Parks: Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park}}</ref>\n\n==Hiking==\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park is known for its redwood groves<ref name=\"Fodor's2010\">{{cite book|author=Fodor's|title=Fodor's Northern California 2011: With Napa, Sonoma, Yosemite, San Francisco & Lake Tahoe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ORayPYO-TvcC&pg=PA95|accessdate=25 December 2011|date=21 December 2010|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=978-1-4000-0503-1|page=94}}</ref> and trail to Pfeiffer Falls. Mud slides caused by the Basin Complex fire necessitated rerouting the Pfeiffer Falls Trail. Reestablishing the old trail, with the wooden foot bridges, was scheduled to begin in 2016.\n\n== Fire impact ==\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park was damaged by the [[Basin Complex Fire]] during June and July 2008, which burned {{convert|162818|acre|km2}} in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/1367/|title=InciWeb the Incident Information System: Basin Complex|website=InciWeb.nwcg.gov|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> Much of the damage was to the outskirts of the park, however, and the campgrounds were able to reopen at the end of July. The Chalk Fire of September and October, which burned an additional {{convert|16269|acre|km2}}, did serious damage to Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park, which was largely closed from September 2008 to May 2009.<ref>{{cite web|date=October 30, 2008|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/1551/|title=InciWeb the Incident Information System: Chalk|website=InciWeb.nwcg.gov|publisher=|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=570}}\n\n{{Protected areas of California|SP}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:State parks of California]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Coast redwood groves]]\n[[Category:Parks in Monterey County, California]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Santa Lucia Range]]\n[[Category:Big Sur]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park\n| iucn_category = III\n| photo = Pfeiffer Beach Stream.jpg\n| photo_caption = Looking back from the beach at Pfeiffer Beach in California\n| map = USA California#USA\n| relief = 1\n| location = [[Monterey County, California]], United States\n| nearest_city = [[Big Sur, California]]\n| coords = {{Coord|36|15|N|121|47|W|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n| area_acre = 1000\n| established =\n| visitation_num =\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[California Department of Parks and Recreation]]\n}}\n\n'''Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park''' is a [[state park]] in [[Monterey County, California|Monterey County]], [[California]], near the area of [[Big Sur]] on the [[U.S. state|state's]] [[Central Coast, California|Central Coast]]. It covers approximately {{convert|1006|acre|km2}} of land. The park is centered on the [[Big Sur River]]. It has been nicknamed a \"mini Yosemite.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seemonterey.com/big-sur-california/pfeiffer-big-sur-state-park-big-sur-california|title= Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Pfeiffer homestead.jpg|thumb|upright|John Pfeiffer's cabin, 2006]]\n\nThe first known European settler in Big Sur was George Davis, who in 1853 claimed a tract of land along the Big Sur River. He built a cabin near the present day site of the beginning of the Mount Manuel Trail.<ref name=\"henson\">{{cite web|last1=Henson|first1=Paul|author2=Donald J. Usner|title=The Natural History of Big Sur|url=http://sulcus.berkeley.edu/wjf/m/NaturalHistoryOfBigSur.pdf|publisher=University Of California Press|access-date=12 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617070622/http://sulcus.berkeley.edu/wjf/m/NaturalHistoryOfBigSur.pdf |archivedate= June 17, 2010|date=1993}}</ref>{{rp|326}} In 1868, Native Americans Manual and Florence Innocenti bought Davis' cabin and land for $50. \n\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park is named after John Pfeiffer, who lived in a cabin on the property beginning in 1884. He was the son of Michael Pfeiffer and Barbara Laquet. The Pfeiffer family family immigrated from France. Their son and his family were among the first European settlers in the area. In the winter of 1869, Michael and Barbara Laquet Pfeiffer were on their way to the south coast of Big Sur when they were forced to stop for the season in the Sycamore Canyon area near present-day Big Sur Village. They liked the area so much they decided against moving south again the following spring. They brought four children with them: Charles, John, Mary Ellen, and Julia. They later had four more:  William, Frank, Flora, and Adelaide. After the [[Homestead Acts#Homestead Act of 1862|Homestead Act of 1862]] was passed by Congress, he filed for patents on his land in 1883 and 1889.<ref>{{cite web |title=Micheal Pfeiffer of Monterey County {{!}} 2 Land Patents |url=https://thelandpatents.com/owners/1112682 |website=The Land Patents |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hikinginbigsur.com/hikes_oakgrove.html|title= Hiking in Big Sur - Oak Grove Trail Loop|website=HikingInBigSur.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Many features in Big Sur are named for the descendants of the Pfeiffers.\n\nIn 1930, John Pfeiffer was offered $210,000 by a developer for his land by a Los Angeles developer who intended to build a subdivision. Pfeiffer wanted to preserve the land he and his family had grown to love, and instead sold {{convert|700|acre|km2}} to the state of California in 1933.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Heid|first1=Analise Elliot|title=Hiking & backpacking Big Sur : a complete guide to the trails of Big Sur, Ventana Wilderness, and Silver Peak Wilderness|date=2013|publisher=Wilderness Press|isbn=978-0899977270|page=84|edition=Second}}</ref>\n\nIn 1934, the [[Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council#History|Monterey Bay Area Council]] built a makeshift Camp Wing within the park, but it was abandoned after the 1937 summer camping season. The next year the Boy Scouts built Camp Esselen at another location within the park. This site was improved until 1945, when limitations of the site, closeness to public camping facilities, and jurisdictional conflicts between the Scouts and the state forced the council to request reimbursement from the state for $8,000 in improvements. The council continued to use the camp until 1953. In 1952, the Scouts began building [[Camp Pico Blanco]], and when that camp was opened in 1954, Camp Esselen was finally closed.<ref name=\"leaders\">{{cite web|url=http://camppicoblanco.org/pico/downloads/2016_camp_pico_blanco_leaders_guide/|title=2017 Camp Pico Blanco Scout Reservation Leader's Guide|publisher=Monterey Bay Area Council, Boy Scouts of America|location=Salinas, California|accessdate=September 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906001953/http://camppicoblanco.org/pico/downloads/2016_camp_pico_blanco_leaders_guide/|archivedate=September 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"men\">{{cite news|url=http://whitestag.org/files/men_in_the_making.pdf|title=The Making of Men|last=Young|first=Alfred|date=July 1963|publisher=Monterey Bay Area Council|location=Salinas, California|accessdate=August 13, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201153140/http://whitestag.org/files/men_in_the_making.pdf|archivedate=December 1, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Overnight stays==\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park has both a hotel (the Big Sur Lodge) and a campground within its boundaries. The campgrounds were closed in the winter of 2008\u20132009 due to the [[Basin Complex Fire]]. The campgrounds have coin-operated showers, bathrooms and a convenience store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seemonterey.com/big-sur-california/pfeiffer-big-sur-state-park-big-sur-california|title= Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park}}</ref> The convenience store also offers WiFi access.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parks.ca.gov/default.asp?page_id=570 |title=California State Parks: Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park}}</ref>\n\n==Hiking==\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park is known for its redwood groves<ref name=\"Fodor's2010\">{{cite book|author=Fodor's|title=Fodor's Northern California 2011: With Napa, Sonoma, Yosemite, San Francisco & Lake Tahoe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ORayPYO-TvcC&pg=PA95|accessdate=25 December 2011|date=21 December 2010|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=978-1-4000-0503-1|page=94}}</ref> and trail to Pfeiffer Falls. Mud slides caused by the Basin Complex fire necessitated rerouting the Pfeiffer Falls Trail. Reestablishing the old trail, with the wooden foot bridges, was scheduled to begin in 2016.\n\n== Fire impact ==\nPfeiffer Big Sur State Park was damaged by the [[Basin Complex Fire]] during June and July 2008, which burned {{convert|162818|acre|km2}} in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/1367/|title=InciWeb the Incident Information System: Basin Complex|website=InciWeb.nwcg.gov|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> Much of the damage was to the outskirts of the park, however, and the campgrounds were able to reopen at the end of July. The Chalk Fire of September and October, which burned an additional {{convert|16269|acre|km2}}, did serious damage to Pfeiffer Big Sur State Park, which was largely closed from September 2008 to May 2009.<ref>{{cite web|date=October 30, 2008|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/1551/|title=InciWeb the Incident Information System: Chalk|website=InciWeb.nwcg.gov|publisher=|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=570}}\n\n{{Protected areas of California|SP}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:State parks of California]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Coast redwood groves]]\n[[Category:Parks in Monterey County, California]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Santa Lucia Range]]\n[[Category:Big Sur]]\n", "name_user": "Btphelps", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pfeiffer_Big_Sur_State_Park"}
{"title_page": "Susan Paterno", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Susan Paterno\n| image       =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:Susan Paterno Live on Bowen RMITV Promo Photo.png|150px]] -->\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Susan Paterno\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = \n| residence   = \n| known_for   = {{hlist|[[Live on Bowen]] 2012 TV variety show|[[Round Ireland with a Fridge]]}}\n| education   = \n| occupation  = Australian actress and TV personality\n| salary      = \n| religion    = \n| years_active = \n| networth    =\n| spouse      = \n}}\n\n'''Susan \"Susie\" Paterno''' is an Australian actress and TV personality. Paterno was a regular cast member of both Eric Bana's comedy sketch show [[Eric (1997 TV series)|Eric]] in 1997 and [[Shaun Micallef]]'s[[The Micallef Programme]] in 1998. She has had roles on Australian TV dramas [[Neighbours]] and [[Blue Heelers]] and has starred in such films as Johannes Roberts New Zealand horror movie [[Darkhunters]]<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0337598/</ref> in 2004 and [[Round Ireland with a Fridge]] in 2010.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1440755/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_5</ref> In 2012 Susan was a co-host of the [[RMITV]] flagship program [[Live on Bowen]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2201812/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Darkhunters]]'' || Carol Miller  ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Round Ireland with a Fridge]]'' || Karen ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paterno, Susan}}\n[[Category:20th-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:RMITV alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing 